\begin_layout Standard
In many applications, it is instructive to study the correlations between
 the PDFs and the experimental observables.
 We review the relevant theoretical framework as presented in Ref.***.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a variable that depends on the PDFs.
 We consider 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as a function of the parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 that define the PDFs at the initial scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\vec{a})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}$
\end_inset

 forms a vector in an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional PDF parameter space, with 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 being the number of free parameters in the global analysis that determines
 these PDFs.
 In the Hessian formalism for the uncertainty analysis developed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pumplin:2001ct"

\end_inset

 and used in all of our recent work, this parton parameter space is spanned
 by a set of orthonormal eigenvectors obtained by a self-consistent iterative
 procedure 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Tung:2006tb,Pumplin:2002vw"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}_{0}$
\end_inset

 represents the best fit obtained with a given set of theoretical and experiment
al inputs, the variation of 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\vec{a})$
\end_inset

 for parton parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}$
\end_inset

 in the neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{a}_{0}$
\end_inset

 is given, within the Hessian approximation, by a linear formula
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta X(\vec{a})=X(\vec{a})-X(\vec{a}_{0})=\vec{\nabla}X|_{\vec{a}_{0}}\cdot\Delta\vec{a},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\nabla}X$
\end_inset

 is the gradient of 
\begin_inset Formula $X(\vec{a}),$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\vec{a}=\vec{a}-\vec{a}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 As explained in detail in Refs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pumplin:2001ct,Pumplin:2002vw,Tung:2006tb"

\end_inset

, the uncertainty range of the PDFs in our global analysis is characterized
 by a tolerance factor 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, equal to the radius of a hypersphere spanned by maximal allowed displacements
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\vec{a}$
\end_inset

 in the orthonormal PDF parameter representation.
 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is determined by the criterion that all PDFs within this tolerance hypersphere
 should be consistent with the input experimental data sets within roughly
 90% c.l.
 The detailed discussions and the specific iterative procedure used to construct
 the eigenvectors can be found in Refs.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pumplin:2001ct,Pumplin:2002vw,Tung:2006tb"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, the results of our uncertainty analysis are characterized by
 
\begin_inset Formula $2N$
\end_inset

 sets of published eigenvector PDF sets along with the central fit.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 PDF sets for each of the 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 eigenvectors, along the 
\begin_inset Formula $(\pm)$
\end_inset

 directions respectively, at the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $|\Delta\vec{a}|=T$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th component of the gradient vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\nabla}X$
\end_inset

 may be approximated by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial X}{\partial a_{i}}\equiv\partial_{i}X=\frac{1}{2}(X_{i}^{(+)}-X_{i}^{(-)}),\label{dXdzi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}^{(+)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}^{(-)}$
\end_inset

 are the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 computed from the two sets of PDFs along the (
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

) direction of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th eigenvector.
 The uncertainty of the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 due to its dependence on the PDFs is then defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta X=\left\vert \vec{\nabla}X\right\vert =\frac{1}{2}\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^{N}\left(X_{i}^{(+)}-X_{i}^{(-)}\right)^{2}},\label{masterDX}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where for simplicity we assume that the positive and negative errors on
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are the same.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

