\begin_layout Standard
The values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta X,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta Y,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\varphi$
\end_inset

 are also sufficient to estimate the PDF uncertainty of any function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X,Y)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 by relating the gradient of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X,Y)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{X}f\equiv\partial f/\partial X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{Y}f\equiv\partial f/\partial Y$
\end_inset

 via the chain rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta f=\left|\vec{\nabla}f\right|=\sqrt{\left(\Delta X\ \partial_{X}f\ \right)^{2}+2\Delta X\ \Delta Y\ \cos\varphi\ \partial_{X}f\ \partial_{Y}f+\left(\Delta Y\ \partial_{Y}f\right)^{2}}.\label{df}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Of particular interest is the case of a rational function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(X,Y)=X^{m}/Y^{n},$
\end_inset

 pertinent to computations of various cross section ratios, cross section
 asymmetries, and statistical significance for finding signal events over
 background processes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Nadolsky:2001yg"

\end_inset

.
 For rational functions Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "df"

\end_inset

) takes the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\Delta f}{f_{0}}=\sqrt{\left(m\frac{\Delta X}{X_{0}}\ \right)^{2}-2mn\frac{\Delta X}{X_{0}}\ \frac{\Delta Y}{Y_{0}}\ \cos\varphi\ +\left(n\frac{\Delta Y\ }{Y_{0}}\right)^{2}}.\label{dfrat}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For example, consider a simple ratio, 
\begin_inset Formula $f=X/Y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f/f_{0}$
\end_inset

 is suppressed (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f/f_{0}\approx\left|\Delta X/X_{0}-\Delta Y/Y_{0}\right|$
\end_inset

) if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are strongly correlated, and it is enhanced (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f/f_{0}\approx\Delta X/X_{0}+\Delta Y/Y_{0}$
\end_inset

) if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are strongly anticorrelated.
\end_layout

